AUDIO: 'Today we are going to create imaginary&nbsp; characters and make them dance. And we’ll&nbsp;&nbsp; use an AI to greatly improve the details&nbsp; in low-quality streamed gaming videos,&nbsp;&nbsp; and we will see if it is possible for a&nbsp; robot to learn to smell. Spoiler alert:&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there is a new AI that has no nose,&nbsp; and yet it can still smell. Kind of. Now, this is an AI paper from 2016. This&nbsp; is what was possible 8 years ago. You could&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take a source video of an amazing dancer,&nbsp; and take a video of yourself moving about,&nbsp;&nbsp; and then, it would transfer&nbsp; these amazing dance moves to you.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But today, not only text to image, but text to&nbsp; video is getting more and more available. This&nbsp;&nbsp; means that you just enter a piece of text, and&nbsp; out comes a video of exactly that. What’s more,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'today, you can do this with free and open&nbsp; source techniques. But if that is possible,&nbsp;&nbsp; does that mean that? Yes, yes it does!'

